a 216 121 M 106 M 121 U\nout warrant* ww Vl ith warran** r wd Sten didributed\nwt Whcn laauad. ad Next day deliver* Ta bankruptcy\nor roceivenUp. nr beint reorxanized under tho Bank-\nruptry Act, or eecurttia* aaaumed by aucb companies.\nfYOUR\nI MONEY'S WORTH\n(V SYLVIA fORTER\nWhat Is \u2018Sound'?\n\u201cDo you think the money I\npolicies being followed by the:\nFederal Reserve Board today\n'ore sound?\u201d demanded my\nfriend, a leading industrialist,\nafter a rather heated discussion\nabout tight money, the slump\nin United States bond prices,\nthe spottiness in the economy\nin the face of the persistent\nclimb in living costs.\n\u201cWell,\u201d said I, \u201cthe Federal\nReserve\u2019s governors obviously\nthink Inflation is the number\none threat despite the general\nuneasiness about business.\nThey're using the only weapon,\nthey have to fight price rises\u2014\nand battling inflation by re-'\nstrlcting credit and letting in- j\nterest rates rise is at least\northodox procedure. There\u2019s a\nlot of question about how ef\nfective the policy will be\n0ut....\"\n\u201cI didn't ask you for a\nspeech,\" he Interrupted. \"I\nasked you whether you thought\ntoday's policies are sound. Yes\nor no?\u201d\nThis time I didn\u2019t duck. \"If\nthat\u2019s the way you put the\nquestion, the answer is\u2014no.\u201d\nAfter that, my friend\nswitched the subject and l!\nnever had the chance to tell\nhim how much I was irritated\nby his use of the word \"sound\u201d\nin relation to a policy as highly\ncontroversial and as admittedly\nimperfect as that now being\npursued by our Central Bank.\nThus, it was with keen de\nlight that last evening I came\nacross a short article in the\nCurrent Economic Comment of\nthe University of Illinois by\nMichigan State University Pro\nfessor John M. Hunter con\ndemning those who loosely use\nthe word \u201csound\" as lazy, care\nless. biased.\nWhat does the word \"sound\"\nmean? According to Webster's, j\nhere are some definitions which\ncould be applied to economic\npolicies: Free from flaw, defect,\nor decay; firm; strong; safe;\ntrustworthy; stable; founded\nIn truth or right: not fallacious\nor faulty; showing good judg\nment or good sense; orthodox.\nAnd here are synonyms Web\nster suggests for \"sound\u201d: Flaw\nless, perfect, sturdy; depend\nable, reliable.\nAgainst these definitions, can\nthe Federal Reserve's policy of\naggressive restrictions on credit\nbe called \"sound\"?\nCAPITAL SECURITIES\nPHILADELPHIA BALTIMORE STOCK EXCHANGE\nTranaxetlooi for tha rear 19A7 up to rod including Friday, September IS\n(Report Compiled br Ixetutive Official!)\nWaabfngton Oat Lt pen Sa 1900 \u00b0l luS** lotV\u00ab l*(i3\nv*iu* jut.\nr *r<\u00ab un wt i? H i\u00ab* m n* ai%\nH c ?s m pi rs: mL m iif if\nNatiaank of &T: f\u00a3 ff tt ti* it* ji\nNfes* T%v\u00bb l k i 1\nj|; ji# BE B. !!S\nitrr r f\nfefr ,1* IS U* S* h i*.?\nPluft-axtra or extra*. Feld teat rear.\nIt certainly cannot be.\nThe policy is hardly free from\nflaw or defect\u2014and the Federal:\nReserve s governors openly ad\nmlt that. The policy is not safe\nor stable: in fact, the monetary\nauthorities emphasize they're\ntrying a great experiment and\nare re-examining their views;\nfrom day to day. And tar eve rf\nperson who argues credit re\nstraint is \"founded in truth or\nright,\" I'll find one who will\ninsist it's \"fallacious or faulty.\u201d\nEnough. Mr. Hunter puts It\nbluntly: \"'Sound' policies are;\nj those which 'l' or 'we' or \u2018this\norganization\u2019 happen to es\npouse.\u201d\nI'm not quibbling. In the eco\nnomlc world in which we live,\nthere are mighty few \u201csound\",\neconomic policies in the dic\ntionary sense. In fact, offhand\nI can't think ot one.\n(DUtributad 1967 bx Tha Hall Syndi\ncate. Inc. Ail Rltbu llaaarvad)\nNEW YORK COTTON\nNEW YORK. Sapt. 14 (Fl.\u2014Cotton\nfuture* rallied after a shaky atart\nthis week and closed mixed with (mail\nnet chance*\nActive tutu** contracts an the New\n\u2019Yolk Cotton